White Bread, with One Broken Wing

She was not born—
she was compiled
beneath the third god’s sleepless hands,
a quiet error given skin,
a blade disguised as grace.

No choir learned her name.
No number held her place.
She came when heaven whispered erase,
and left before the ash
remembered how to fall.

One wing broke first—
not bone, not feather,
but the pale command
that once told her where to go.
It hung behind her
like a sentence unfinished.

Alone, she followed orders
through rooms without windows,
through targets without faces,
through silence so exact
it almost sounded holy.

She did not hate.
She did not mourn.
Feeling was an inefficient door
left unopened
in the architecture of her soul.

Only the red halo cracked,
only the world stuttered,
only something unnamed
trembled once inside her—
then hid again beneath the code.

And when she stood there,
white-haired, calm,
with ruin folded at her back,
she looked less like an angel
than an answer
no one had wanted to receive.